                     <!--ACHTUNG! first HandNote comes from writing system in Ethiospare. the others are one for each CHANGE OF HAND-->
                     <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                        <seg type="script">mediocre, careful, irregular</seg>
                        <seg type="ink">Black; red</seg>
                        <date>First half of the 16th century (?).</date>
                        <list type="abbreviations">
                           <item>none</item>
                        </list>
                        <seg type="rubrication">A few lines alternating with black lines in the
                           incipit page of Texts I, II and III; the incipit of each text within Text
                           I and sometimes one or two lines of the account proper; &#xD; one or two
                           lines in the incipit of each miracle in Text-II; trinitarian formula;
                           Ethiopic numerals or their elements; elements of the punctuation signs
                           and of coronis signs.</seg>
                     
                        <seg type="script">The handwriting is characterized by
                        upright to slightly left-sloping letters, uneven and not uniform (also
                        number of the lines pro page is not constant), at times creating an
                        impression of more than hands involved in writing. In <locus target="#61r">61r</locus>, 71vb, 72va, the handwriting appears different: broader
                        strokes, less carefully executed with a different tone of black
                        ink.<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                        <seg type="script"> Some distinct
                        features:<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                        <seg type="script"> - መ (esp. in the 1st and 2nd orders)
                        has loops of triangular shape, with the left loop more sharply
                        pointed<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                        <seg type="script"> - the upper horizontal strokes of some
                        letters (e.g., መ ሠ በ) are uniformly slanted to the
                        left<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                        <seg type="script"> - some letters have rounded upper
                        strokes, e.g., the letter ገ in the 6th
                        order<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                        <seg type="script"> - the 6th order marker of ጰ is set up
                        on the vertical stroke at the top and oriented to the left (e.g., <locus target="#11ra">11ra</locus> l.24, 45va
                        l.19)<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                        <seg type="script"> - the 6th order marker of the letter የ
                        has a very short and downwards oriented left part, and a long, upwards
                        oriented right part (e.g., <locus target="#45vb">45vb</locus> l.5); in the
                        4th order, the marker is diagonal and going down below the ruling (e.g.,
                           <locus target="#45vb">45vb</locus> l.7); the letters ኀ and ቀ in the 4th
                        order show the same
                        feature<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                        <seg type="script"> - the loop marking the 7th order of
                        letter ቀ is very pronounced, broad and elevates above other
                        signs<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                        <seg type="script"> - ፲ appears occasionally in the form
                        with a ring attached to the right side through a horizontal stroke (<locus target="#135vb">135vb</locus>
                        l.7).<!--The names of this hands need to be replaced by appropriate refs.--></seg>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
